diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from getting oxygen and nutrients. Brain cells begin to die in minutes. Symptoms can include sudden numbness, confusion, trouble speaking, seeing or walking, and severe headache.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: Multiple sclerosis (MS) is a potentially disabling disease of the brain and spinal cord (central nervous system). The immune system attacks the protective sheath (myelin) that covers nerve fibers, causing communication problems between your brain and the rest of your body. Symptoms include fatigue, numbness and weakness, coordination and balance issues, and problems with speech.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A migraine can cause severe throbbing pain or a pulsing sensation, usually on one side of the head. It's often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and extreme sensitivity to light and sound. Migraine attacks can cause significant pain for hours to days and can be so severe that the pain is disabling. Warning symptoms known as aura may occur before or with the headache.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a transient ischemic attack is a brief period of symptoms similar to those you'd have in a stroke. A TIA doesn't cause permanent damage. They are caused by a temporary decrease in blood supply to part of the brain, which may last as little as five minutes.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A brain tumor is a mass or growth of abnormal cells in your brain or close to your brain. Many different types of brain tumors exist. Some brain tumors are noncancerous (benign), and some brain tumors are cancerous (malignant). Brain tumors can begin in your brain (primary brain tumors), or cancer can begin in other parts of your body and spread to your brain (secondary, or metastatic, brain tumors).

diagnoses.name: Meniere's Disease
diagnoses.description: Meniere's disease is a disorder of the inner ear that can lead to dizzy spells (vertigo) and hearing loss. In most cases, Meniere's disease affects only one ear. It can cause sudden episodes of vertigo, along with a ringing sound or noise in the ear (tinnitus), hearing loss that can become permanent, and a feeling of fullness in the ear.

diagnoses.name: Vestibular Neuritis
diagnoses.description: Vestibular neuritis is inflammation of the vestibular nerve, a nerve in the ear that helps control balance. This condition can cause sudden, severe vertigo and imbalance without hearing loss. It is often triggered by a viral infection.

diagnoses.name: Vertebrobasilar Insufficiency
diagnoses.description: Vertebrobasilar insufficiency is a condition in which blood flow through the back part of the brain (vertebrobasilar system) is reduced, which can lead to symptoms such as dizziness, vision problems, coordination problems, and slurred speech.

diagnoses.name: Acoustic Neuroma
diagnoses.description: An acoustic neuroma is a noncancerous growth that develops on the eighth cranial nerve, which runs from your inner ear to your brain. The symptoms of an acoustic neuroma can include hearing loss, ringing in one ear, dizziness, and balance problems.

diagnoses.name: Brain Abscess
diagnoses.description: A brain abscess is a collection of pus, immune cells, and other material in the brain, usually from a bacterial or fungal infection. Brain abscesses can cause symptoms similar to a stroke, including headaches, seizures, and problems with speech, vision, and movement.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that affects the brain and spinal cord, causing a range of neurological symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of migraine that involves visual disturbances (such as scotomas) and other neurological symptoms prior to the headache.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A medical condition where poor blood flow to the brain results in cell death, causing symptoms depending on the area affected.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: Abnormal and uncontrolled cell division in the brain that can compress and/or damage normal brain tissue and function.

diagnoses.name: Myasthenia Gravis
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune neuromuscular disease that causes weakness in the skeletal muscles responsible for breathing and moving parts of the body.

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barre Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder in which the body's immune system attacks the nerves, leading to muscle weakness and sometimes paralysis.

diagnoses.name: Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS)
diagnoses.description: A neurodegenerative disease that affects nerve cells in the brain and the spinal cord, causing loss of muscle control.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a transient episode of neurological dysfunction caused by the loss of blood flow to the brain, spinal cord, or retina, without acute infarction.

diagnoses.name: Neurosyphilis
diagnoses.description: A bacterial infection of the brain or spinal cord that can occur in people with untreated syphilis, causing a wide range of symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.description: Vitamin B12 is crucial for the normal function of the brain and the nervous system and its deficiency can lead to neurological symptoms such as paraesthesia and dysarthria.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A condition where poor blood flow to the brain results in cell death, causing symptoms such as weakness, headache, and aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a minibar stroke, it temporarily blocks blood flow to the brain, causing similar symptoms as a stroke but typically lasting less than 24 hours.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: An abnormal growth of cells in the brain that can cause pressure and lead to symptoms like headache, weakness, and language difficulties.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A type of headache that can be severe and often accompanied by nausea and sensitivity to light. Some forms of migraine may also include aura, which can mimic stroke symptoms including weakness and speech disturbances.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that affects the brain and spinal cord, leading to symptoms such as weakness, speech difficulties, and fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Encephalitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the brain, often caused by an infection. Symptoms can include headache, seizures, weakness, and cognitive deficits.

diagnoses.name: Brain Abscess
diagnoses.description: A collection of pus that develops in the brain due to infection, causing swelling and symptoms such as headache, fever, and in some cases, speech problems and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy
diagnoses.description: A disorder in which nerve cell activity in the brain is disturbed, leading to seizures. Some types of seizures can result in aphasia and postictal weakness.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the membranes covering the brain and spinal cord. It can lead to severe headache, fever, and in more severe cases, neurological deficits, including aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Hemorrhagic Stroke
diagnoses.description: Occurs when a blood vessel in the brain ruptures, leading to bleeding in or around the brain. Symptoms can mirror those of an ischemic stroke, including weakness, headache, and language difficulties.

diagnoses: Drug Reaction with Eosinophilia and Systemic Symptoms (DRESS)

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can affect multiple systems including the skin, joints, kidneys, blood cells, brain, heart, and lungs. The combination of hemolytic anemia, nonscarring alopecia, arthropathy, and discoid rash is characteristic of this condition.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that primarily affects joints but can also cause a variety of systemic symptoms. While hemolytic anemia and arthropathy are common, nonscarring alopecia and discoid rash are less typical but can occur.

diagnoses.name: Discoid Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic skin condition of sores with inflammation and scarring favoring the face, ears, and scalp. While primarily affecting the skin, patients may also experience systemic symptoms similar to those of SLE.

diagnoses.name: Sjogren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that attacks the glands that provide lubrication to the eyes and mouth. It can be associated with other immunological diseases that could explain a broader symptom spectrum including hemolytic anemia and arthropathy.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Hemolytic Anemia
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders characterized by hemolytic anemia, where the immune system mistakenly destroys red blood cells. Association with other autoimmune disorders could explain the additional symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Lupus Vasculitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of blood vessels that can occur in the context of lupus, leading to a range of symptoms including skin manifestations, arthritis, and anemia.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare autoimmune disorder that may feature signs and symptoms of lupus, scleroderma, polymyositis, and rheumatoid arthritis, including those mentioned.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease marked by muscle weakness and a distinctive skin rash, which could include discoid rash. Hemolytic anemia and arthropathy are less common but possible in association with the disease's systemic effects.

diagnoses.name: Evans Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare autoimmune disorder characterized by the combination of immune thrombocytopenia (ITP) and autoimmune hemolytic anemia, which may coexist with other autoimmune conditions presenting with the given symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: Certain types of lymphoma can present with hemolytic anemia and systemic symptoms. Although less common, arthropathy, nonscarring alopecia, and skin manifestations like a discoid rash can occur in the setting of lymphoma.
